  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "Oil painting on canvas (52.1 × 41.4 cm, signed and dated 1825) by Dutch painter and actor **Johannes Rienksz. Jelgerhuis** (1770–1836). The painting depicts the **choir of the Nieuwe Kerk (New Church) in Delft**, looking toward the monumental mausoleum of **Willem I, Prince of Orange** (William the Silent, 1533–1584), designed by **Hendrick de Keyser** (1614–1621) and completed by his son **Pieter de Keyser** in 1623. The painting belongs to the tradition of Dutch topographical church-interior painting stretching from the 17th-century Delft School (Houckgeest, De Witte, Van Vliet) to 19th-century Romanticism. Staffage figures include a man and young boy with a dog. The canvas was painted in the year Jelgerhuis exhibited in Haarlem. The Rijksmuseum holds a related chalk/watercolor drawing dated 1824 (RP-T-00-1820) that appears to be a direct preparatory study for this painting, and a second related work from July 1819 (RP-T-1921-334).",
      "classified_as": [
